(a) the angles of the triangle are in arithmetic progression;

(b) the common tangent to the nine-point circle and the in-circle is parallel to the Euler line.

2011.statement_latex:
Let ABC be a triangle each of whose angles is greater than 30\degree. Suppose a circle, with centre T, cuts the segments BC in P, Q; CA in K, L; and AB in M, N, such that P, Q, K, L, M, N are on the circle in counter-clock-wise direction in that order. Suppose further that the triangles TQK, TLM and TNP are all equilateral. Prove that:

(i) the radius of the circle is $\frac{2abc}{a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 4\sqrt{3}\Delta}$;

(ii) $a \cdot AT = b \cdot BT = c \cdot CT$.

2013.statement_latex:
Let $h \ge 3$ be an integer and $X$ the set of all positive integers that are greater than or equal to $2h$. Let $S$ be a nonempty subset of $X$ such that the following two conditions hold:

\begin{itemize}
\item if $a + b \in S$ with $a \ge h, b \ge h$, then $ab \in S$;
\item if $ab \in S$ with $a \ge h, b \ge h$, then $a+b \in S$.
\end{itemize}

Prove that $S = X$.
